<td align="center">
<div class="poemtitle">Trust is a Rusty Bucket</div> 
<br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('cantor')">by K.R. Copeland</a> <br>
<br>
<br>
<table cellpadding="20" cellspacing="0"><tr><td>
But then, I don’t know jack<br>
or Jill for that matter. Matter of fact,<br>
I don’t know diddly. Simply put<br>
the years of rain have eroded the hand-<br>
held water holder I used to tote.<br>
&nbsp;<br>
Up and down the hill I’d fill and refill,<br>
empty and empty again. That was then,<br>
&nbsp;<br>
before I fell. Now, I settle<br>
for a sip at a time, which is fine,<br>
I guess. It helps the hours pass.<br>
Alas, dear Liza, I knew her well.<br>
&nbsp;<br><br>
<font size="-1">Previously published, <I>The American Drivel Review</I>, Summer 2005.</font><br>
</td>
<td align="right" valign="top"><img src="images/trustisarustybucket.jpg"><br><span class="byartist">Patricia Wallace Jones</span></td>
</tr></table>
</td>
</tr>
